trination and definately the victors version. And if schools are place for learning, isn't having an opportunity to learn about religions, something that creates such a strong response both from the religious and secular (as can be seen here), by virtue of extra-curricular type clubs, a good thing? No, of course not. It is much better that others spiritual beliefs be kept behind closed doors and cave entrances, as some have suggested, so that we may fear and mock them, safe in our ignorance. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="785" language="en" documentId="1428" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="chemo25" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/tempers-flare-over-prayer-in-schools-1.1104775" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1428" notes="" title="Tempers flare over prayer in schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="130"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="131" end="785"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>